without a little bit of a
summary to get you warmed

00:10:08.120 --> 00:10:08.243
up for the dramatic performance.

00:10:10.130 --> 00:10:12.663
So Mr. Anderson, would
you help me out?

00:10:13.140 --> 00:10:13.273
&gt;&gt; M.T. Anderson: Is my mike on?

00:10:15.140 --> 00:10:15.226
Okay. For those of you who have
not yet tasted the delights

00:10:18.920 --> 00:10:19.120
of the Exquisite Corpse Adventure

00:10:20.920 --> 00:10:24.920
&gt;&gt; We offer a summary of dangerous
exploits and daring deeds.

00:10:27.440 --> 00:10:28.440
&gt;&gt; The long

00:10:30.210 --> 00:10:32.676
&gt;&gt; M.T. Anderson: And
the short of it.

00:10:33.260 --> 00:10:36.393
The Exquisite Corpse
Adventure, the story begins

00:10:37.180 --> 00:10:37.713
with a train rushing
through the night.

00:10:39.180 --> 00:10:41.913
Our heroes, Joe and
Nancy, orphaned twins.

00:10:42.760 --> 00:10:46.960
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Tobin, you and
I, we, we could be Joe and Nancy.

00:10:47.160 --> 00:10:48.160
&gt;&gt; M.T. Anderson: You
want us to be the twins?

00:10:49.160 --> 00:10:50.493
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Yes.

00:10:51.160 --> 00:10:52.560
&gt;&gt; M.T. Anderson: I'm always
having trouble thinking

00:10:53.160 --> 00:10:54.053
of us as the same species.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:55.000


00:10:55.660 --> 00:10:56.860
[ Audience moans ]

00:11:03.060 --> 00:11:04.793
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Forget it.

00:11:05.060 --> 00:11:06.726
Continue, Tobin Anderson.

00:11:07.060 --> 00:11:08.786
&gt;&gt; M.T. Anderson: Our heroes, Joe
and Nancy, receive a birthday card

00:11:09.800 --> 00:11:12.666
from their previously
presumed dead parents.

00:11:13.070 --> 00:11:13.476
Their task, limb by limb they must
piece together the Exquisite Corpse,

00:11:17.330 --> 00:11:21.196
a top secret robot, and rescue
their aforementioned parents

00:11:21.260 --> 00:11:24.993
from certain oblivion, trapped
outside of space and time.

00:11:26.310 --> 00:11:26.710
Bolstered in their quest by
a roller-skating, a pirate,

00:11:29.510 --> 00:11:30.096
a talking pig -- are
you getting all this --

00:11:31.790 --> 00:11:32.796
a pack of wolves, an elephant, a
door mouse, a misfortune teller,

00:11:35.050 --> 00:11:39.050
and a bobble-headed robot, aided
by the mysterious red arrows

00:11:39.920 --> 00:11:40.000
on their little toes,
a crystal ball,

00:11:42.240 --> 00:11:42.763
and handy skills acquired growing
up in the Sick and Tired Circus,

00:11:46.050 --> 00:11:47.850
lion taming, knife throwing

00:11:48.360 --> 00:11:48.713
and trapeze flying --
still on board with me?

00:11:50.940 --> 00:11:51.736
They travel into the woods under the
sea, up to the sky, back and forth

00:11:54.810 --> 00:11:58.143
through time, fending off
hunger, fatigue, despair,

00:11:58.150 --> 00:11:58.283
sibling separation,
poisoned meatballs,

00:12:00.550 --> 00:12:03.150
electronic pitchforks,
lances and prods.

00:12:03.750 --> 00:12:07.750
They battle a narcoleptic clown,
a pack of thieves and dozens

00:12:08.330 --> 00:12:12.396
of tentacled Eggy-Thing alien
invaders who disguise themselves

00:12:12.580 --> 00:12:13.326
as gorillas, monster wolves and
squid beasts, torturing others

00:12:15.900 --> 00:12:17.833
with bad puns and lame yolks.

00:12:18.860 --> 00:12:18.926
I hope you're getting all this.

00:12:20.860 --> 00:12:24.126
Only our heroes, Nancy and
Joe Sloppy and the Sick

00:12:25.460 --> 00:12:28.993
and Tired Circus stand
between those alien Eggy-Things

00:12:29.720 --> 00:12:31.120
and world domination.

00:12:31.720 --> 00:12:33.293
Because you know, a story's not
a story unless someone's trying

00:12:34.280 --> 00:12:36.280
for world domination, we feel.

00:12:36.430 --> 00:12:39.496
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: That was
a really long summary.

00:12:41.270 --> 00:12:41.670
&gt;&gt; M.T. Anderson: You can do better?

00:12:43.270 --> 00:12:43.403
Let's hear your shorter version.

00:12:45.270 --> 00:12:46.403
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: All right,
ladies and gentleman,

00:12:47.270 --> 00:12:49.003
I need a little help here?

00:12:49.270 --> 00:12:50.470
Ready? Here we go.

00:12:51.270 --> 00:12:51.536
Orphans no more, Nancy and Joe set

00:12:53.270 --> 00:12:53.366
out to save their parents
and fight their foes.

00:12:56.240 --> 00:12:58.973
They pieced together
the Exquisite Corpse,

00:13:04.470 --> 00:13:05.203
fight invading aliens,
running and warped.

00:13:06.470 --> 00:13:06.670
Will they triumph, we don't know.

00:13:08.470 --> 00:13:10.540
But I'd lay good money
on Nancy and Joe.

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:10.000


00:13:10.970 --> 00:13:11.970
[ Cheering ]

00:13:14.080 --> 00:13:17.346
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: We have a
little commercial break.

00:13:17.710 --> 00:13:21.643
I would like anyone in the
audience whose birthday is today,

00:13:22.350 --> 00:13:26.283
and maybe even on stage whose
birthday is today, to stand up

00:13:31.170 --> 00:13:33.703
and wave their hands
wildly in the air.

00:13:39.840 --> 00:13:41.240
Hey, look, we got on.

00:13:42.720 --> 00:13:43.853
&gt;&gt; Happy birthday

00:13:44.720 --> 00:13:45.720
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: To you,
happy birthday to you,

00:13:46.720 --> 00:13:48.453
happy birthday dear Jimmy,

00:13:48.720 --> 00:13:49.006
and everyone else,
happy birthday to you.

00:13:51.100 --> 00:13:52.100
[ Applause ]

00:13:53.100 --> 00:13:54.966
&gt;&gt; I really appreciate that.

00:13:57.100 --> 00:13:58.100
Thank you.

00:13:59.720 --> 00:14:01.453
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: All right.

00:14:01.720 --> 00:14:02.580
It's almost time to hear
the very last episode

00:14:03.860 --> 00:14:03.946
of the Exquisite Corpse Adventure.

