And what happens when he juggles?

00:16:19.760 --> 00:16:21.760
&gt;&gt; Oh, I don't know that part.

00:16:21.920 --> 00:16:23.186
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Oh.

00:16:23.920 --> 00:16:24.986
[ Bicycle horn ]

00:16:25.920 --> 00:16:26.253
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Katherine Paterson?

00:16:27.920 --> 00:16:28.520
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson:
He goes to sleep.

00:16:29.920 --> 00:16:31.120
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: He goes
to sleep when he juggles.

00:16:31.920 --> 00:16:32.920
Oh, great.

00:16:36.210 --> 00:16:38.343
Do we have a body part up there?

00:16:41.870 --> 00:16:43.470
Okay, question number 2.

00:16:45.290 --> 00:16:47.156
Which of the twins is older?

00:16:47.290 --> 00:16:48.290
Nancy or Joe?

00:16:49.290 --> 00:16:50.356
[ Bicycle horn ]

00:16:51.290 --> 00:16:52.556
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Oh.

00:16:53.290 --> 00:16:54.290
James?

00:16:55.290 --> 00:16:56.890
&gt;&gt; James Ransome: Nancy.

00:16:57.290 --> 00:16:58.623
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Yes.

00:16:59.290 --> 00:17:00.090
&gt;&gt; James Ransome: She's
as shocked as I am.

00:17:01.290 --> 00:17:02.823
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: I know.

00:17:03.290 --> 00:17:05.290
And how -- does anyone know how
much older Nancy is than Joe?

00:17:05.290 --> 00:17:07.290
&gt;&gt; James Ransome: Two minutes.

00:17:07.290 --> 00:17:09.156
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Two minutes?

00:17:09.290 --> 00:17:09.356
&gt;&gt; James Ransome: I don't know.

00:17:11.290 --> 00:17:12.356
[ Bicycle horn ]

00:17:13.290 --> 00:17:14.823
&gt;&gt; I thought it was 15.

00:17:15.290 --> 00:17:17.090
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: 15 minutes.

00:17:17.290 --> 00:17:18.356
No. Anyone else?

00:17:19.290 --> 00:17:19.623
&gt;&gt; I think it's less than a minute.

00:17:21.290 --> 00:17:21.356
I'll bet on less than a minute.

00:17:23.290 --> 00:17:25.090
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: 90 seconds.

00:17:25.290 --> 00:17:26.290
&gt;&gt; 90 seconds?

00:17:27.290 --> 00:17:29.090
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: 90 seconds.

00:17:29.290 --> 00:17:30.290
&gt;&gt; Oh.

00:17:31.290 --> 00:17:33.090
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Question 3.

00:17:33.290 --> 00:17:35.556
The character in James Ransome
drawing takes Nancy and Joe to spy

00:17:35.290 --> 00:17:37.156
on the conference of aliens,

00:17:37.290 --> 00:17:38.223
where they see the aliens'
true shape for the first time.

00:17:40.090 --> 00:17:43.756
Who is that character and
what is the alien's true name?

00:17:43.910 --> 00:17:44.976
[ Bicycle horn ]

00:17:45.910 --> 00:17:47.510
&gt;&gt; James Ransome: Hathi.

00:17:47.910 --> 00:17:49.376
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Hathi.

00:17:49.910 --> 00:17:51.176
Did you draw Hathi?

00:17:51.910 --> 00:17:51.976
&gt;&gt; James Ransome: No, I didn't.

00:17:53.910 --> 00:17:54.910
Oh, -- you

00:17:55.910 --> 00:17:57.776
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: That's okay.

00:17:57.910 --> 00:17:59.310
&gt;&gt; James Ransome: No, today
I didn't draw him, but I

00:17:59.910 --> 00:18:01.576
&gt;&gt; Oh, I thought you did.

00:18:01.910 --> 00:18:03.376
I came in late, sorry.

00:18:03.910 --> 00:18:05.310
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Okay.

00:18:05.910 --> 00:18:07.110
Question number 4.

00:18:07.910 --> 00:18:09.310
Where did the twins find
Roberta, the robot's, legs?

00:18:09.910 --> 00:18:10.910
&gt;&gt; The what?

00:18:11.910 --> 00:18:14.643
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Roberta the robot's
legs, where did the twins find them?

00:18:13.910 --> 00:18:14.976
[ Bicycle horn ]

00:18:15.910 --> 00:18:16.043
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Linda was first.

00:18:17.910 --> 00:18:18.110
&gt;&gt; Linda Sue Park: Under the sea.

00:18:19.910 --> 00:18:21.176
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: No.

00:18:21.910 --> 00:18:22.910
&gt;&gt; Oh, oh, oh.

00:18:23.910 --> 00:18:24.976
[ Bicycle horn ]

00:18:25.910 --> 00:18:27.443
&gt;&gt; They hopped down on the
cradle of sun, didn't they?

00:18:27.910 --> 00:18:29.776
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Yes, they were
clowns running through time.

00:18:29.910 --> 00:18:31.243
&gt;&gt; Oh, that's right.

00:18:31.910 --> 00:18:33.643
&gt;&gt; Wait a second, what was

00:18:33.910 --> 00:18:35.776
&gt;&gt; The arms were on the sea.

00:18:35.910 --> 00:18:37.710
&gt;&gt; What was on the chimney?

00:18:37.910 --> 00:18:38.910
&gt;&gt; The arms.

00:18:39.910 --> 00:18:40.910
Break a leg.

00:18:41.910 --> 00:18:44.576
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Question 5, when the
twins discover a gingerbread house

00:18:43.910 --> 00:18:45.710
in the woods, starving Joe
runs to it as a source of food,

00:18:45.910 --> 00:18:46.643
but Nancy tries to
hold them back, saying,

00:18:47.910 --> 00:18:49.843
don't you remember the story?

00:18:49.910 --> 00:18:50.110
What story is Nancy referring to?

00:18:51.910 --> 00:18:52.976
[ Bicycle horn ]

00:18:53.910 --> 00:18:55.376
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: James?

00:18:55.910 --> 00:18:56.043
&gt;&gt; James Ransome: Hansel Gretel.

00:18:57.910 --> 00:18:59.243
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Yes.

00:18:59.910 --> 00:19:01.043
I know everyone here has
read Hansel and Gretel.

00:19:01.910 --> 00:19:04.243
Question 6, how does Joe battle
the squid to recover the lost key?

00:19:03.910 --> 00:19:05.043
[ Bicycle horns ]

00:19:05.910 --> 00:19:07.776
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Oh, my gosh.

00:19:07.910 --> 00:19:08.776
These national ambassadors
are so brilliant.

00:19:09.910 --> 00:19:10.910
Yes, Katherine?

00:19:11.910 --> 00:19:14.176
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: I think I
go start on James and Linda Sue.

00:19:13.910 --> 00:19:14.910
Arm wrestling.

00:19:15.910 --> 00:19:16.243
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Arm wrestling, yes.

00:19:17.910 --> 00:19:18.110
This is the last question, Gerry.

00:19:19.910 --> 00:19:19.976
Do we have it almost assembled?

00:19:21.910 --> 00:19:23.510
&gt;&gt; Gerry: One more page.

00:19:23.910 --> 00:19:25.643
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: The heart.

00:19:25.910 --> 00:19:26.176
We need to give Roberta her heart.

00:19:27.910 --> 00:19:29.910
When Roberta the Robot has
finally been completely assembled,

00:19:29.910 --> 00:19:30.376
what last object do
Nancy and Joe need

00:19:31.910 --> 00:19:32.843
to find before they can
rescue their parents?

00:19:33.910 --> 00:19:34.776
Oh, no, it's that National
Ambassador again.

00:19:35.910 --> 00:19:36.376
&gt;&gt; Wait, that was a
real timid squeak.

00:19:37.910 --> 00:19:38.910
[ Laughter ]

00:19:39.910 --> 00:19:40.310
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: The last egg?

00:19:41.910 --> 00:19:42.310
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: The
last, the last --

00:19:43.910 --> 00:19:46.243
what last object do Nancy and Joe
need to find before they collect

00:19:45.910 --> 00:19:46.976
[ Bicycle horn ]

00:19:47.910 --> 00:19:49.243
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Yes.

00:19:49.910 --> 00:19:50.110
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: I do know.

00:19:51.910 --> 00:19:53.576
I did this thing, though.

00:19:53.910 --> 00:19:54.043
The head, the head of the robot.

00:19:55.910 --> 00:19:56.643
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Oh,
no, guys, she's wrong.

00:19:57.910 --> 00:19:58.043
The National Ambassador's wrong.

00:19:59.910 --> 00:20:01.643
&gt;&gt; The Ambassador's wrong.

00:20:01.910 --> 00:20:02.910
&gt;&gt; The heart.

00:20:03.910 --> 00:20:04.910
&gt;&gt; The brain.

00:20:05.910 --> 00:20:06.910
&gt;&gt; The heart

00:20:07.910 --> 00:20:08.910
&gt;&gt; No.

00:20:09.910 --> 00:20:10.910
&gt;&gt; Memory.

00:20:11.910 --> 00:20:13.843
&gt;&gt; Do you want me to give you

00:20:13.910 --> 00:20:14.043
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: The door.

00:20:15.910 --> 00:20:17.576
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: The door.

00:20:17.910 --> 00:20:18.910
&gt;&gt; The door.

00:20:19.910 --> 00:20:20.043
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: That's the door.

00:20:21.910 --> 00:20:22.976
[ Bicycle horn ]

00:20:23.910 --> 00:20:25.243
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Yes.

00:20:25.910 --> 00:20:28.243
Now, we have successfully assembled
the Exquisite Corpse, Roberta,

00:20:27.910 --> 00:20:30.510
the top secret robot and the moment
we have been waiting for all year.

00:20:29.910 --> 00:20:31.310
I met a teacher right in
front of the audience here,

00:20:31.910 --> 00:20:34.576
who her class has been waiting all
year to hear this last final episode

00:20:33.910 --> 00:20:34.110
of the Exquisite Corps Adventure.

00:20:35.910 --> 00:20:37.510
The name of the title of the
last episode is Over Easy,

00:20:37.910 --> 00:20:38.176
and it is written and now directed

00:20:39.910 --> 00:21:28.286
as a stage play by
Katherine Paterson.

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:55.000


00:20:41.910 --> 00:20:42.910
[ Applause ]

00:20:43.910 --> 00:20:45.376
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Tobin?

00:20:45.910 --> 00:20:47.776
&gt;&gt; M.T. Anderson: All right.

00:20:47.910 --> 00:20:49.843
On one side of the forest, a
train rushes through the night,

00:20:49.910 --> 00:20:51.243
a train filled with lions
and elephants and clowns.

00:20:51.910 --> 00:20:53.710
And on the other side of the
forest, leaping and frothing,

00:20:53.910 --> 00:20:54.510
yellow and sticky,
hurling their unfried

00:20:55.910 --> 00:20:57.576
and unfriendly splattering
cells through the underbrush,

00:20:57.910 --> 00:20:59.043
a tide of mucusy monsters
storms into the world.

00:20:59.910 --> 00:21:01.576
And gathering around a hut,
near a broken train trestle,

00:21:01.910 --> 00:21:03.243
a few friends stand between
an invasion of raw eggs

00:21:03.910 --> 00:21:05.643
and the fate of the world.

00:21:05.910 --> 00:21:06.910
In a case like this,
there's no sunny side up.

00:21:07.910 --> 00:21:10.110
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: If you
have been following this adventure

00:21:09.910 --> 00:21:12.043
as closely as the authors have
hoped, you will not be surprised

00:21:11.910 --> 00:21:13.710
to know at this moment, a
supreme crisis, Nancy the brave,

00:21:13.910 --> 00:21:16.043
the intelligent, the moral Nancy,
took charge of the situation.

00:21:15.910 --> 00:21:16.976
&gt;&gt; First of all, Pirandello
must stop the train

00:21:17.910 --> 00:21:20.176
and tell the ringmaster to set
the tent up as quickly as possible

00:21:19.910 --> 00:21:20.510
with the large opening
facing the woods.

00:21:21.910 --> 00:21:23.376
It's so the aliens will all
come rushing in after us.

00:21:23.910 --> 00:21:25.976
&gt;&gt; We're going to be standing
in there, like waiting for them?

00:21:25.910 --> 00:21:27.510
&gt;&gt; Good thinking, Nancy.

00:21:27.910 --> 00:21:29.243
We should all go now and
help them set up the tent.

00:21:29.910 --> 00:21:31.643
We can do it in that grassy
spot right beside the tracks.

00:21:31.910 --> 00:21:33.510
There's no time to lose.

00:21:33.910 --> 00:21:36.376
&gt;&gt; M.T. Anderson: Everyone, except
Genius Kelly, who was very speedy

00:21:35.910 --> 00:21:37.443
when he chose, swung up on
Hathi, the Elephant's back,

00:21:37.910 --> 00:21:37.980
and the great beast
raced towards the spot.

00:21:40.640 --> 00:21:41.813
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: The train had
barely shuttered to a stop when all

00:21:44.200 --> 00:21:44.673
of the members of the circus
had been hustled off and led

00:21:47.460 --> 00:21:50.460
by the shouts by the
ringmaster, went to work.

00:21:51.280 --> 00:21:51.296
As you can imagine,
persons who belong

00:21:53.730 --> 00:21:57.063
to a circus are well
practiced in setting up a tent

00:21:57.330 --> 00:22:01.663
in expeditious manner, in less
time than it would take you to sing

00:22:02.440 --> 00:22:06.573
"99 Bottles of Beer on the Wall"
followed by all four versus of

00:22:06.880 --> 00:22:07.593
"The Star Spangled Banner"
(provided you know all four verses),

00:22:10.300 --> 00:22:11.900
the Big Top was erected.

00:22:13.020 --> 00:22:14.323
&gt;&gt; M.T. Anderson: With no time
to spare, however, indeed,

00:22:15.450 --> 00:22:16.676
Hathi and the other friendly
pachyderms had barely hammered

00:22:18.090 --> 00:22:18.233
down the last tent pole when
the invasion of Eggy-Things,

00:22:21.680 --> 00:22:21.983
having cast off all their disguises,
came streaming through the woods

00:22:25.910 --> 00:22:26.856
and slurped into the tent at such
a speed that our friends winced

00:22:29.230 --> 00:22:32.763
at the schlap against the
canvas on the opposite side.

00:22:33.530 --> 00:22:35.996
The ringmaster was
already on the job.

00:22:36.040 --> 00:22:40.306
"Ladies, Gentlemen, gentle beasts,
and uh -- Super Ova," we have,

00:22:41.540 --> 00:22:46.206
if a bit hastily, assembled for you
the greatest little show on earth."

00:22:46.510 --> 00:22:48.443
&gt;&gt; "Forget the show on earth.

00:22:48.510 --> 00:22:50.643
We want extraterrestrial jokes."

00:22:52.510 --> 00:22:53.776
[ Audience booing ]

00:22:57.090 --> 00:23:01.223
&gt;&gt; "Ah, of course, but ours are
old and tired and very earthly.

00:23:01.430 --> 00:23:02.696
We need your help."

00:23:03.720 --> 00:23:06.586
&gt;&gt; "Yes. Give us your
yolks, and (yuk, yuk),

00:23:08.700 --> 00:23:11.033
the yolk will be on you, old woman.

00:23:11.810 --> 00:23:16.143
After the yolks we will give you
our very specially imported brand

00:23:17.210 --> 00:23:18.210
of salmonella.

00:23:19.330 --> 00:23:23.263
You will die slowly and painfully,
which will be fun to see,

00:23:25.740 --> 00:23:28.140
but we won't be able to linger long.

00:23:28.440 --> 00:23:32.040
We have to spread our contagion
throughout the planet."

00:23:33.570 --> 00:23:34.383
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: With
these words of mucusy menace,

00:23:36.490 --> 00:23:41.156
the Eggy-Things started across the
width of the tent toward our heroes.

00:23:41.210 --> 00:23:42.210
&gt;&gt; "No, no.

00:23:43.210 --> 00:23:44.743
Ve only vant da yolks."

00:23:45.270 --> 00:23:45.470
The silly ova began laughing
and separating themselves,

00:23:48.670 --> 00:23:50.536
the yellows from the whites.

00:23:50.670 --> 00:23:51.670
"

00:23:52.670 --> 00:23:53.670
&gt;&gt; "Toodle-oo.

00:23:55.430 --> 00:23:56.430
&gt;&gt; "Be ready.

00:23:57.620 --> 00:24:00.820
As soon as we stop yoking
around, slither hither.

00:24:01.170 --> 00:24:02.436
We got a yob to do.

00:24:03.170 --> 00:24:04.170
Yuk, yuk."

00:24:05.500 --> 00:24:06.566
&gt;&gt; "Don't worry.

00:24:07.500 --> 00:24:09.100
We're right behind you."

00:24:10.360 --> 00:24:13.826
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: "Not
bad for one so colorless.

00:24:14.030 --> 00:24:17.230
But somehow, we expected
better from you yellows.

00:24:17.530 --> 00:24:21.330
If the condemned prisoner can
request one last good smoke,

00:24:23.520 --> 00:24:26.453
we'd like to go out with
one last good joke."

00:24:27.970 --> 00:24:28.673
&gt;&gt; The eggy folks -- the eggy
yolks couldn't bear to be sneered

00:24:31.400 --> 00:24:34.466
at by a pig and began to
scramble for the honor

00:24:34.760 --> 00:24:36.960
of delivering the last good joke.

00:24:37.290 --> 00:24:38.490
&gt;&gt; "Knock, knock."

00:24:39.290 --> 00:24:40.423
&gt;&gt; "Who's there?"

00:24:41.290 --> 00:24:42.290
&gt;&gt; "Oregon."

00:24:43.290 --> 00:24:44.356
&gt;&gt; "Oregon who?"

00:24:45.290 --> 00:24:45.350
&gt;&gt; "Ore-e-gonna take
over the world?"

00:24:47.630 --> 00:24:48.696
&gt;&gt; "You betcha."

00:24:49.630 --> 00:24:51.830
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: The yuks
that followed this bad joke were

00:24:51.630 --> 00:24:53.496
so loud they shook the tent.

00:24:56.340 --> 00:24:57.340
[ Laughing ]

00:24:58.340 --> 00:24:59.806
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: But
to the invaders' distress,

00:25:00.340 --> 00:25:00.410
not one of our heroes
even cracked a smile.

00:25:03.070 --> 00:25:04.536
The yokes tried again.

00:25:05.070 --> 00:25:06.270
&gt;&gt; "Knock, knock."

00:25:07.070 --> 00:25:08.203
&gt;&gt; "Who's there?"

00:25:09.070 --> 00:25:10.070
&gt;&gt; "Scieszka."

00:25:11.070 --> 00:25:12.270
&gt;&gt; "Scieszka how?"

00:25:13.070 --> 00:25:14.203
&gt;&gt; "Gesundheidt."

00:25:15.070 --> 00:25:15.336
&gt;&gt; "No more shouting out answers."

00:25:17.070 --> 00:25:19.003
&gt;&gt; M.T. Anderson: "I'm sorry.

00:25:19.070 --> 00:25:20.870
But I do want to have one last
laugh before it's all over,

00:25:21.070 --> 00:25:21.136
and I already heard that joke."

00:25:23.070 --> 00:25:24.936
The yokes went into a huddle,
or for those readers familiar

00:25:25.070 --> 00:25:25.773
with the game, into
sort of a rugby scrum.

00:25:27.100 --> 00:25:27.116
At last one yoke seemed
to separate from the mass.

00:25:30.350 --> 00:25:33.016
There was the sound
of a throat clearing.

00:25:33.370 --> 00:25:34.370
&gt;&gt; "A hum.

00:25:35.370 --> 00:25:37.103
We are going to have a yoke
-- we're going to have a joke

00:25:37.370 --> 00:25:39.236
or if you prefer a yoke off.

00:25:39.370 --> 00:25:43.103
The winner will have the honor
of making the final joke."

00:25:43.160 --> 00:25:44.010
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson:
Genius Kelly sighed loudly

00:25:45.510 --> 00:25:47.776
and pretended to examine his hoof.

00:25:47.940 --> 00:25:50.873
The elephants sighed
even more loudly and lay

00:25:51.880 --> 00:25:54.613
down on the ground and
pretended to snore.

00:25:55.660 --> 00:25:56.460
&gt;&gt; "If you noodle noggins have
any desire to live long enough

00:25:58.860 --> 00:26:02.126
for the last laugh, this
will be the last chance."

00:26:04.910 --> 00:26:04.956
&gt;&gt; M. T. Anderson: With that he/she
or it ducked back into the scrum

00:26:09.330 --> 00:26:09.536
and soon there arose from
that side of the tent

00:26:12.190 --> 00:26:14.656
such a cacophony of
screeches and yuks

00:26:15.220 --> 00:26:16.686
[ Screeches and yuks ]

00:26:17.220 --> 00:26:17.890
&gt;&gt; M.T. Anderson: that our heroes
put their hands, hooves, paws,

00:26:20.750 --> 00:26:23.483
feet or trunks over
their ears in defense.

00:26:23.910 --> 00:26:24.910
&gt;&gt; "Look."

00:26:25.910 --> 00:26:27.580
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: Joe looked
and what he saw astounded him.

00:26:28.440 --> 00:26:31.906
A mass of yellows was going
around faster and faster.

00:26:33.010 --> 00:26:36.610
The more the yolks yelled,
the faster around they went.

00:26:36.830 --> 00:26:38.830
The scrum was being scrambled.

00:26:39.390 --> 00:26:40.390
[ Laughing ]

00:26:41.390 --> 00:26:42.123
&gt;&gt; M.T. Anderson: "Those
stupid yokes are,

00:26:43.390 --> 00:26:45.190
are beating themselves up."

00:26:45.390 --> 00:26:46.323
Nancy glanced over at
the waiting egg whites.

00:26:47.390 --> 00:26:48.670
If they had had eyes, their eyes
would have been popping out.

00:26:50.110 --> 00:26:51.110
&gt;&gt; "Quick.

00:26:52.110 --> 00:26:53.843
Everyone go into your act.

00:26:54.110 --> 00:26:55.443
As fast as you can."

00:26:56.110 --> 00:26:56.776
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson:
Suddenly, the Sick

00:26:58.110 --> 00:26:58.976
and Tired Circus was
sick and tired no more.

00:27:00.110 --> 00:27:00.950
Genius Kelly danced and whirled
into his magical judo act.

00:27:03.070 --> 00:27:06.003
The twins did loopdy
loops on the high wires;

00:27:06.050 --> 00:27:06.126
the elephants swung their trunks
about and then their huge rear ends

00:27:10.440 --> 00:27:12.306
with their tails a-twirling.

00:27:12.440 --> 00:27:12.880
The Ringmaster spun
around with his whip going

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:17.066
at least ninety miles per hour.

00:27:17.600 --> 00:27:18.140
Roberta grabbed the hand
of the headless woman

00:27:20.060 --> 00:27:20.136
who in turn grabbed a monkey's
paw that grabbed the hand

00:27:23.650 --> 00:27:24.133
of the bearded woman who
grabbed a string of chimps

00:27:26.500 --> 00:27:26.650
who grabbed a seal's flipper
who flapped Roberta's other hand

00:27:30.350 --> 00:27:30.973
and they raced a ring a round a
rosie about the startled whites

00:27:33.860 --> 00:27:36.926
who grew paler and fuller
of air by the moment.

00:27:38.140 --> 00:27:39.143
&gt;&gt; M.T. Anderson: Every now
and then a piteous wail arose

00:27:40.870 --> 00:27:43.470
over the racket of
frenzied circus acts.

00:27:43.540 --> 00:27:44.540
&gt;&gt; "Help"

00:27:45.540 --> 00:27:47.140
&gt;&gt; "Stop! I'm air sick!"

00:27:47.540 --> 00:27:48.330
&gt;&gt; "We'll mend our wicked way
if you'll stop whipping us!"

00:27:50.550 --> 00:27:51.656
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: But
no one even paused to listen.

00:27:53.110 --> 00:27:57.043
Our heroes knew better than to
trust even the pallid portion

00:27:57.660 --> 00:27:59.460
of the villainous invaders.

00:27:59.660 --> 00:28:04.260
And before long all the whites had
been whipped into a giant meringue,

00:28:04.260 --> 00:28:06.593
making the lions roar with delight.

00:28:07.250 --> 00:28:08.250
[ Roar ]

00:28:09.250 --> 00:28:09.716
&gt;&gt; M.T. Anderson: "Fire
juggling act!"

00:28:11.250 --> 00:28:12.303
The clowns grabbed the torches
and juggled and breathed fire

00:28:14.130 --> 00:28:14.770
onto the newly whipped
meringue until it stood

00:28:16.490 --> 00:28:18.290
up in beautiful ecru peaks.

00:28:18.490 --> 00:28:19.490
&gt;&gt; "Mmmmm.

00:28:20.490 --> 00:28:23.023
Scrambled eggs for the main course
and a lovely meringue for dessert.

00:28:22.490 --> 00:28:24.890
It looks almost good enough to eat."

00:28:30.440 --> 00:28:30.573
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: "Almost."

00:28:32.440 --> 00:28:34.516
&gt;&gt; M.T. Anderson: Meanwhile Angel
had been busy summoning the Cradle

00:28:34.830 --> 00:28:35.830
of Time.

00:28:36.830 --> 00:28:38.696
With the elephants' help all
the scrambled yolks were piled

00:28:38.830 --> 00:28:42.030
into the cradle topped
off by the giant meringue.

00:28:42.270 --> 00:28:43.406
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: For a few
moments our exhausted friends

00:28:45.200 --> 00:28:49.400
watched and listened, the beasts
panting, the people perspiring,

00:28:50.640 --> 00:28:52.640
but they needn't have worried.

00:28:52.640 --> 00:28:55.506
There wasn't even a
whimper from the cradle.

00:28:55.930 --> 00:29:00.263
Neither the scrambled yolks nor
the whipped whites showed any sign

00:29:00.580 --> 00:29:01.780
of reconstituting.

00:29:02.670 --> 00:29:03.543
The Eggy-Things that had threatened
them for so long had been done

00:29:06.130 --> 00:29:09.196
in by their own rotten
humor and the cleverness

00:29:09.720 --> 00:29:11.653
of our little band of heroes.

00:29:11.920 --> 00:29:14.720
&gt;&gt; "Now, off you go,
back to the big bang."

00:29:15.100 --> 00:29:16.233
&gt;&gt; "Not so fast!"

00:29:17.210 --> 00:29:17.476
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: The ominous

00:29:19.210 --> 00:29:22.343
but familiar voice belonged
of course, to Boppo.

00:29:25.570 --> 00:29:27.036
[ Booing and hissing ]

00:29:27.570 --> 00:29:29.570
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: He had
one giant clown foot atop Libby

00:29:29.570 --> 00:29:33.436
Verrie-Sloppy and another
holding Professor Alistair Sloppy

00:29:33.530 --> 00:29:34.530
on the ground.

00:29:35.530 --> 00:29:35.600
Both the twins' parents
appeared to be asleep.

00:29:38.460 --> 00:29:40.260
&gt;&gt; "They're under my power.

00:29:40.460 --> 00:29:41.460
While the rest of you were
busy whipping up trouble,

00:29:42.860 --> 00:29:43.580
I managed to hypnotize this
pair with my best juggling at.

00:29:45.940 --> 00:29:46.646
It was all done with mirrors -- very
skillfully, if I do say so myself.

00:29:49.900 --> 00:29:53.166
Now, I will rescue my
comrades and throw these two

00:29:53.490 --> 00:29:53.890
into the cradle of their own making.

00:29:55.490 --> 00:29:59.490
Then I will extract one final
bomb from my pocket which will,

00:30:00.590 --> 00:30:04.923
for sentimental reasons, go off
in exactly 47 ticks of the clock."

00:30:04.990 --> 00:30:05.990
&gt;&gt; "Oh, no.

00:30:06.990 --> 00:30:09.390
Not that stupid juggling act again."

00:30:09.870 --> 00:30:13.736
&gt;&gt; "Just when I thought
misfortune had landed on its head."

00:30:15.170 --> 00:30:18.036
&gt;&gt; "I never trusted
that red-nosed ruffian."

00:30:19.050 --> 00:30:21.050
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: "Oink."

00:30:21.050 --> 00:30:22.050
&gt;&gt; "Huh?"

00:30:23.050 --> 00:30:24.850
&gt;&gt; "Lullaby and goodnight."

00:30:25.050 --> 00:30:26.650
&gt;&gt; "With roses bedight."

00:30:27.930 --> 00:30:31.596
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: Before
they got to the third line

00:30:31.990 --> 00:30:35.856
about the lilies, Boppo had
sunk to the earth with a snore.

00:30:37.080 --> 00:30:37.746
&gt;&gt; M.T. Anderson: With
catlike quickness,

00:30:39.080 --> 00:30:39.593
Angel threw the evil clown and
his ticking bomb into the cradle

00:30:42.700 --> 00:30:42.873
and sent him and the whole alien
brunch racing toward the creation

00:30:46.860 --> 00:30:47.926
of the universe.

00:30:48.860 --> 00:30:50.950
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: It happened
so fast that they all simply stared

00:30:51.370 --> 00:30:55.570
at the empty space in the sky
that the cradle had flown through.

00:30:57.030 --> 00:30:58.030
&gt;&gt; "Hurray."

00:30:59.030 --> 00:31:00.096
&gt;&gt; M.T. Anderson: Everyone
turned in amazement.

00:31:01.030 --> 00:31:01.563
The tiny voice had
come from the throat

00:31:03.030 --> 00:31:06.096
of the headless woman --
her first spoken word.

00:31:06.620 --> 00:31:06.626
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: A baby
monkey began to clap his tiny hands

00:31:10.880 --> 00:31:10.886
and soon they were all cheering
and dancing and shouting

00:31:14.540 --> 00:31:18.473
and hugging one another in
relief that the danger had passed

00:31:18.640 --> 00:31:21.306
and in joy at what
they had accomplished.

00:31:22.510 --> 00:31:23.510
[ Cheering ]

00:31:50.040 --> 00:31:51.130
&gt;&gt; And now we come to the part
of the story no one likes much --

00:31:53.150 --> 00:31:54.133
the farewells between friends who
have suffered and struggled and,

00:31:56.500 --> 00:31:58.300
yes, even laughed together.

00:31:58.500 --> 00:31:59.966
&gt;&gt; M.T. Anderson: Pirandello
headed off to the forest

00:32:00.500 --> 00:32:00.606
where he found Orlando munching
on gummi bears and took her home.

00:32:04.660 --> 00:32:08.193
Angel and Sybil said goodbye
and started off together,

00:32:08.300 --> 00:32:09.380
as Angel had become quite fond of
the Misfortune Teller and determined

00:32:11.820 --> 00:32:14.153
to protect her from any misfortunes

00:32:14.580 --> 00:32:15.046
that still lurked in
her neighborhood.

00:32:16.580 --> 00:32:18.446
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: The last
departing pair were Roberta

00:32:18.580 --> 00:32:19.713
and Genius Kelly.

00:32:20.580 --> 00:32:21.336
Roberta had cleverly undone
Boppo's hypnotic spell

00:32:23.090 --> 00:32:24.690
over the Senior Sloppys.

00:32:25.090 --> 00:32:28.023
When their friends and
ours had escorted them

00:32:29.870 --> 00:32:32.336
to the door before
Pirandello's shack,

00:32:33.260 --> 00:32:34.193
the professor gave me
a lovely little speech,

00:32:35.260 --> 00:32:38.593
thanking the robot handsomely
for all she had done,

00:32:39.250 --> 00:32:41.183
and then adding, a big sadly:

00:32:41.250 --> 00:32:41.830
&gt;&gt; "My dear, you are
no longer a corpse,

00:32:43.270 --> 00:32:45.470
as exquisite as you were and are.

00:32:45.510 --> 00:32:45.866
You are free to go back
to that other dimension

00:32:48.220 --> 00:32:52.353
where you will find others of
your rare kind that I constructed

00:32:52.640 --> 00:32:54.506
in my years behind the door.

00:32:55.010 --> 00:32:58.276
They will welcome you as
the hero you have become.

00:32:59.100 --> 00:32:59.146
Take this wonderful
pig back with you,

00:33:01.520 --> 00:33:02.363
as he and you belong in
that other dimension.

00:33:03.610 --> 00:33:03.883
He will serve as a companion and a
reminder of all you have both done

00:33:07.870 --> 00:33:12.203
to save not only the sloppy family,
but all human and animal kind.

00:33:14.590 --> 00:33:14.796
The key which you have you will
take back with you through the door.

00:33:18.850 --> 00:33:22.050
Please lock it behind you
and throw it away, for,

00:33:22.110 --> 00:33:25.776
though the Eggy-Things no
longer exist in that dimension

00:33:25.840 --> 00:33:27.840
or in this one, I am convinced

00:33:28.770 --> 00:33:33.036
that there should be no more
trafficking between our two worlds."

00:33:35.090 --> 00:33:36.490
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson:
Genius Kelly opened his snout

00:33:37.090 --> 00:33:41.290
to make a long speech, but Roberta
punched him on the short ribs

00:33:42.570 --> 00:33:46.370
and smilingly urged him toward
the door, though she paused

00:33:46.670 --> 00:33:49.403
on the threshold to
hug the twins and say:

00:33:49.630 --> 00:33:53.163
&gt;&gt; "Now I know I have a
heart, because it's breaking."

00:33:53.220 --> 00:33:54.220
&gt;&gt; Oh, man.

00:33:55.220 --> 00:33:55.666
&gt;&gt; It was all Nancy could
do to keep from weeping.

00:33:58.040 --> 00:34:00.906
Even brave Joe was seen
to wipe away a tear.

00:34:01.360 --> 00:34:03.293
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: "Wait!

00:34:03.360 --> 00:34:04.160
I have to tell the
twins their true names."

00:34:05.360 --> 00:34:05.963
&gt;&gt; "Nancy and Joe are
not our real names?"

00:34:07.490 --> 00:34:09.290
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: "No.

00:34:09.490 --> 00:34:10.490
Your true names

00:34:11.490 --> 00:34:12.623
[ Clears throat ]

00:34:13.490 --> 00:34:14.823
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: "are
Josephus and Natochka."

00:34:15.490 --> 00:34:16.490
&gt;&gt; "What?"

00:34:17.490 --> 00:34:19.090
&gt;&gt; "I'm sorry, children.

00:34:19.490 --> 00:34:21.156
We repented as soon as we
filed the birth certificates."

00:34:21.490 --> 00:34:23.023
&gt;&gt; "That's why we've always
called you Joe and Nancy."

00:34:23.490 --> 00:34:23.536
&gt;&gt; "Then it's okay if we
just stay Joe and Nancy?"

00:34:26.710 --> 00:34:27.976
&gt;&gt; "Perfectly okay.

00:34:28.710 --> 00:34:32.443
Thank you, G.K., for all you
have done for our children."

00:34:34.730 --> 00:34:35.930
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson:
"May I beg a small favor?"

00:34:36.730 --> 00:34:37.730
&gt;&gt; "Certainly."

00:34:38.730 --> 00:34:40.263
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: "I
know it sounds preposterous,

00:34:40.730 --> 00:34:42.196
but could I have one last
joke to send me on my way?"

00:34:42.730 --> 00:34:42.930
&gt;&gt; M.T. Paterson: "Knock, knock."

00:34:44.730 --> 00:34:45.996
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson:
"Who may I ask is calling?"

00:34:46.730 --> 00:34:48.330
&gt;&gt; M.T. Paterson: "G.K."

00:34:48.730 --> 00:34:48.996
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: "G.K. who?"

00:34:50.730 --> 00:34:52.930
&gt;&gt; M.T. Paterson: "Gee, Kan't you
stay with us a little longer?"

00:34:52.730 --> 00:34:54.063
&gt;&gt; A fat tear rolled down
the porker's black snout.

00:34:54.730 --> 00:34:54.996
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: "Very good.

00:34:56.730 --> 00:34:58.330
I almost wish I could, but
as you know, I must return."

00:34:58.730 --> 00:35:01.063
&gt;&gt; M.T. Paterson: With that, he
waived a hoof and followed Roberta

00:35:00.730 --> 00:35:01.996
through the door which
closed soundly behind them.

00:35:02.730 --> 00:35:03.993
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: Suddenly
Joe, who could never remain gloomy

00:35:05.800 --> 00:35:09.133
for very long, whipped
something out of his pocket.

00:35:09.170 --> 00:35:13.303
It was the birthday card that
had started all their adventures.

00:35:13.480 --> 00:35:14.030
&gt;&gt; "Mom, Dad, when we got your
card, we were in the middle

00:35:16.730 --> 00:35:17.130
of a really special birthday party."

00:35:18.730 --> 00:35:20.663
&gt;&gt; "The Elephant Clown Party!

00:35:20.730 --> 00:35:21.330
In all the excitement
I forgot about it.

00:35:22.730 --> 00:35:25.526
&gt;&gt; "Yeah, yeah."

00:35:21.000 --> 00:35:22.000


00:35:24.890 --> 00:35:25.890
[ Screaming ]

00:35:27.050 --> 00:35:28.450
&gt;&gt; "We didn't forget.

00:35:29.050 --> 00:35:30.516
Come back to the tent.

00:35:31.190 --> 00:35:32.523
Everything is ready.

00:35:33.190 --> 00:35:35.790
We'll give you the
party of your lives."

00:35:36.720 --> 00:35:38.186
&gt;&gt; M.T. Anderson: Now, we
don't have time to tell you

00:35:38.720 --> 00:35:40.453
about the wonderful party.

00:35:40.720 --> 00:35:42.520
You'll just have to use your
imagination to picture clowns

00:35:42.720 --> 00:35:43.346
and elephants and seals and
lions and a bearded woman

00:35:45.560 --> 00:35:46.146
and the headless woman and
monkeys and chimps and every person

00:35:49.040 --> 00:35:50.060
and creature determined to give
the beloved twins the greatest time

00:35:52.420 --> 00:35:54.220
of their eleven years, even

00:35:54.420 --> 00:35:56.243
if in their hearts they knew
it was not only a birthday bash

00:35:56.530 --> 00:35:57.930
but a farewell party.

00:35:58.530 --> 00:36:00.116
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: When it
was over, and Nancy and Joe turned

00:36:01.210 --> 00:36:05.943
for the last worst goodbye to Hathi
and all their friends of the circus,

00:36:06.340 --> 00:36:09.473
the loving pachyderm said
to the Sloppy parents:

00:36:09.820 --> 00:36:12.086
&gt;&gt; "There's no need for you to go.

00:36:13.620 --> 00:36:15.686
Please make your home with us."

00:36:15.750 --> 00:36:18.216
&gt;&gt; "Joe and Nancy are
already family."

00:36:18.350 --> 00:36:19.650
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: The Senior
Sloppys looked at the twins and then

00:36:21.650 --> 00:36:25.516
into the pleading eyes of every
person and beast assembled.

00:36:25.870 --> 00:36:26.870
&gt;&gt; "Why not?

00:36:27.870 --> 00:36:29.336
I could put my inventive
mind to work among you all."

00:36:29.870 --> 00:36:30.870
&gt;&gt; "Why not?

00:36:31.870 --> 00:36:33.203
I've always longed to ride
a bareback on elephants.

00:36:33.870 --> 00:36:35.536
And I'm a terrible cook."

00:36:35.870 --> 00:36:37.070
&gt;&gt; "Yeah, why not?

00:36:37.870 --> 00:36:40.936
The villains are gone
and our parents are here.

00:36:41.020 --> 00:36:42.030
That was all that was wrong with
the Sick and Tired Circus --

00:36:44.010 --> 00:36:46.343
villains here and parents missing."

00:36:46.660 --> 00:36:48.313
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: Nancy
stroked the place on her arm

00:36:48.740 --> 00:36:50.940
where the wolf had scratched her.

00:36:51.160 --> 00:36:51.743
The house with a picket
fence and two parents

00:36:53.510 --> 00:36:56.576
with their twins no
longer seemed so desirable.

00:36:57.010 --> 00:37:00.410
Wasn't a circus the perfect
home for a girl who was,

00:37:01.050 --> 00:37:03.450
at least for the present, part wolf?

00:37:03.780 --> 00:37:07.913
And besides, she had promised
the wolves to speak out for them.

00:37:08.690 --> 00:37:09.690
&gt;&gt; "Why not?"

00:37:10.690 --> 00:37:12.156
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson:

00:37:12.690 --> 00:37:13.606
Hathi encircled the four
Sloppys with her warm trunk.

00:37:15.240 --> 00:37:16.773
&gt;&gt; "Then it's settled."

00:37:19.010 --> 00:37:20.210
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: I
won't say it was the end

00:37:21.010 --> 00:37:21.276
of all their adventures, for Nancy
and Joe were an adventurous pair,

00:37:25.210 --> 00:37:25.420
but it brings to a close the
Exquisite Corpse Adventure

00:37:28.600 --> 00:37:29.600
&gt;&gt; Wow.

00:37:30.600 --> 00:37:31.000
&gt;&gt; -- evil conquered, family united,

00:37:32.600 --> 00:37:35.000
and friends who lived,
I'm quite sure

00:37:35.840 --> 00:37:37.306
&gt;&gt; Happily ever after.

00:37:39.510 --> 00:37:40.510
[ Applause ]

00:37:46.040 --> 00:37:47.440
&gt;&gt; Good job, my boys.

00:37:48.040 --> 00:37:48.280
&gt;&gt; Thank you, sir.

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:50.000


00:37:50.540 --> 00:37:51.540
[ Laughter ]

00:37:56.350 --> 00:37:57.616
&gt;&gt; Yo, Mary Brigid.

00:37:58.350 --> 00:37:59.350
Nice job.

00:38:00.350 --> 00:38:02.216
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Thanks, Tim.

00:38:02.350 --> 00:38:03.606
We actually finished before
we thought we were going to,

00:38:04.760 --> 00:38:08.226
and it's so rare that kids
have so many distinguished

00:38:09.010 --> 00:38:12.876
and talented authors and
illustrators on stage at one time.

