Are there any questions
you would like to ask any

00:38:16.120 --> 00:38:18.186
of our authors or illustrators?

00:38:18.790 --> 00:38:19.790
Anybody? Yes.

00:38:21.360 --> 00:38:23.160
Okay, this is the question.

00:38:27.460 --> 00:38:28.860
And what's your name?

00:38:29.460 --> 00:38:30.726
This is from Annie.

00:38:31.460 --> 00:38:33.593
How did we get the story online?

00:38:36.850 --> 00:38:38.716
Anybody want to answer that?

00:38:39.070 --> 00:38:40.536
Oh, I can answer that.

00:38:41.070 --> 00:38:42.536
&gt;&gt; John Cole: Perfect.

00:38:43.070 --> 00:38:45.003
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: We got the story
online because as Mr. Cole,

00:38:45.070 --> 00:38:46.240
Dr. Cole had mentioned, the
National Children's Book

00:38:47.300 --> 00:38:47.833
and Literacy Alliance has
been working with the Center

00:38:50.300 --> 00:38:50.366
for the Book for over 10 years.

00:38:52.300 --> 00:38:55.566
We actually were the 10
o'clock event 10 years ago

00:38:56.060 --> 00:38:59.993
at the very first National Book
Festival, so it's wonderful.

00:39:00.090 --> 00:39:02.823
And we wanted to come
up with a great idea

00:39:04.170 --> 00:39:04.370
that would get kids reading
and get kids writing,

00:39:07.170 --> 00:39:08.100
and we thought the best way to do
that would be to create a wonderful,

00:39:10.840 --> 00:39:14.573
whacky, entertaining story
that would last all year long.

00:39:14.730 --> 00:39:15.796
And it's worked.

00:39:16.730 --> 00:39:18.183
It's been quite successful, and
it's been a wonderful partnership.

00:39:19.610 --> 00:39:21.810
So make sure you get to Read.gov.

00:39:21.810 --> 00:39:25.876
And if you haven't read the
episodes, they are there for free.

00:39:27.230 --> 00:39:27.563
&gt;&gt; How did we get the story online?

00:39:29.230 --> 00:39:30.040
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Oh, how did
we get the story online?

00:39:31.820 --> 00:39:32.286
&gt;&gt; John Cole: We got
the story online.

00:39:33.820 --> 00:39:35.620
It was through Mary Brigid.

00:39:35.820 --> 00:39:37.553
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Literally,

00:39:37.820 --> 00:39:38.886
like literally how did
we get the story online?

00:39:39.820 --> 00:39:40.820
Oh, my God.

00:39:41.820 --> 00:39:41.953
Well, I guess that's a technical

00:39:43.820 --> 00:39:44.820
&gt;&gt; Jeremy?

00:39:45.820 --> 00:39:46.953
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Yeah,
it's a technical question.

00:39:47.820 --> 00:39:47.926
They wrote the episodes, and
then every two weeks we sent them

00:39:51.780 --> 00:39:54.313
by computer to the
Library of Congress,

00:39:57.550 --> 00:40:02.350
and the magical technology people at
the Library of Congress typed it all

00:40:05.250 --> 00:40:08.450
up and got it right onto
the computer, like that.

00:40:09.030 --> 00:40:09.126
We woke up every second
Friday morning

00:40:11.400 --> 00:40:15.533
and there was a whole new episode
and a whole new illustration.

00:40:16.330 --> 00:40:17.360
&gt;&gt; M.T. Anderson: People who haven't
seen it, it actually looks like a --

00:40:20.100 --> 00:40:21.833
you can read it as a book.

00:40:22.130 --> 00:40:25.063
It looks like a virtual
book on the Internet,

00:40:25.310 --> 00:40:26.473
so you can actually read
it in sort of book format.

00:40:27.480 --> 00:40:27.980
&gt;&gt; Timothy Basil Ering: When
you first get to that home page,

00:40:30.980 --> 00:40:33.246
you'll see all the episodes listed

00:40:34.500 --> 00:40:37.100
and who wrote them
and illustrated them.

00:40:40.130 --> 00:40:44.063
And there's actually a part
where you can click onto hear it

00:40:47.190 --> 00:40:49.456
and a part to click on to read it.

00:40:50.170 --> 00:40:53.570
And when you do, you'll end
up at that virtual book,

00:40:59.990 --> 00:41:02.590
and there's an arrow
where you can click

00:41:03.060 --> 00:41:05.326
to go back and forth in the pages.

00:41:06.840 --> 00:41:08.306
It's really well done.

00:41:08.840 --> 00:41:12.506
And all the readers who read
the episodes are excellent,

00:41:14.350 --> 00:41:15.483
beautifully read.

00:41:16.350 --> 00:41:16.750
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: That was great, Tim.

00:41:18.350 --> 00:41:20.216
You did much better than me.

00:41:20.350 --> 00:41:21.616
All right, any, any

00:41:22.350 --> 00:41:25.483
&gt;&gt; Timothy Basil Ering:
I was impressed with it.

00:41:25.930 --> 00:41:27.346
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Any other kids
have questions, you can walk right

00:41:28.780 --> 00:41:29.626
up to one of the two
microphones in the aisles.

00:41:31.000 --> 00:41:33.733
Be brave. Your mom and
dad are going to be

00:41:35.790 --> 00:41:37.856
so proud if you ask a question.

00:41:37.930 --> 00:41:39.263
Here comes somebody.

00:41:39.930 --> 00:41:41.463
What's your first name?

00:41:41.930 --> 00:41:43.530
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth: Elizabeth.

00:41:43.930 --> 00:41:45.196
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: And where
are you from, Elizabeth?

00:41:45.930 --> 00:41:47.463
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth: Virginia.

00:41:47.930 --> 00:41:49.596
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Virginia.

00:41:49.930 --> 00:41:51.663
Elizabeth's from Virginia.

00:41:51.930 --> 00:41:53.330
What's your question?

00:41:53.930 --> 00:41:54.730
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth: I wondered
when we'll be able

00:41:55.930 --> 00:41:56.530
to get the book of
the Exquisite Corpse.

00:41:57.930 --> 00:42:01.263
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: When you'll
be able to get the book

00:42:02.470 --> 00:42:04.136
for the Exquisite Corpse?

00:42:04.930 --> 00:42:05.526
&gt;&gt; Elizabeth: Yeah,
when are you getting it?

00:42:07.200 --> 00:42:08.003
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: I think
you'll be able to get the book

00:42:09.930 --> 00:42:12.863
for the Exquisite Corpse
right here next year

00:42:14.250 --> 00:42:16.250
at the National Book Festival.

00:42:16.390 --> 00:42:17.390
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson:
So come back next year.

00:42:18.390 --> 00:42:18.813
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: And just think,
we'll have all kinds of authors

00:42:22.100 --> 00:42:24.966
and illustrators again,
and you can get tons

00:42:25.940 --> 00:42:28.340
of their signatures all at one time.

00:42:28.860 --> 00:42:30.793
&gt;&gt; It will also be in stores.

00:42:31.650 --> 00:42:32.346
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: It will
also be in stores, yes.

00:42:34.020 --> 00:42:35.486
&gt;&gt; And online as well.

00:42:36.020 --> 00:42:36.353
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: And online as well,

00:42:38.020 --> 00:42:38.620
and also if you don't
have it this year,

00:42:40.020 --> 00:42:40.886
make sure you get those
posters at the back.

00:42:42.020 --> 00:42:42.086
And you could take two posters.

00:42:44.020 --> 00:42:45.886
Any of the kids can take two
posters -- one for their home,

00:42:46.020 --> 00:42:46.486
and one to take to
school and show off

00:42:48.020 --> 00:42:48.420
to their teacher when
they get there.

00:42:50.020 --> 00:42:50.420
Any more? Oh, there's one over here.

00:42:52.020 --> 00:42:53.020
Who are you?

00:42:54.020 --> 00:42:55.020
&gt;&gt; Nell: Nell.

00:42:56.020 --> 00:42:57.420
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Nell?

00:42:58.020 --> 00:42:59.020
&gt;&gt; Nell: Yeah.

00:43:00.020 --> 00:43:01.620
I live in Massachusetts?

00:43:02.020 --> 00:43:03.020
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

00:43:04.020 --> 00:43:04.486
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: We
love Massachusetts.

00:43:06.020 --> 00:43:06.153
&gt;&gt; Nell: My mom works in Boston.

00:43:08.020 --> 00:43:09.020
&gt;&gt; Pardon?

00:43:10.020 --> 00:43:10.153
&gt;&gt; Nell: My mom works in Boston.

00:43:12.020 --> 00:43:12.820
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: In the
Cradle of Democracy.

00:43:14.020 --> 00:43:15.020
&gt;&gt; Nell: Yeah.

00:43:16.020 --> 00:43:18.153
But why didn't you just release
it as a book to start off with?

00:43:18.020 --> 00:43:18.620
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Why
didn't we release it

00:43:20.020 --> 00:43:21.886
as a book to start off with?

00:43:22.020 --> 00:43:22.953
Well, actually, a little
bit of history here.

00:43:24.020 --> 00:43:25.886
There's a real famous author

00:43:26.020 --> 00:43:27.286
that you'll be reading
soon named Charles Dickens,

00:43:28.020 --> 00:43:30.553
and over 100 years ago, he got all
kinds of people reading by putting

00:43:30.020 --> 00:43:30.286
up a book one episode at the time,

00:43:32.020 --> 00:43:33.753
in what in those days was high
technology -- a newspaper.

00:43:34.020 --> 00:43:34.086
And now, we did the same thing.

00:43:36.020 --> 00:43:38.553
We put one episode up at a time,
and we've been building the audience

00:43:38.020 --> 00:43:39.886
and building the audience 'til
I think Library of Congress,

00:43:40.020 --> 00:43:41.820
we are averaging in some months
over 120,000 hits a month.

00:43:42.020 --> 00:43:44.086
And that's just -- we figure
that a lot of those were teachers

00:43:44.020 --> 00:43:46.620
and librarians who were going back
and sharing the book with the kids.

00:43:46.020 --> 00:43:47.020
So our low-ball estimate
is that over 500,000,

00:43:48.020 --> 00:43:49.953
possibly up to a million kids

00:43:50.020 --> 00:43:52.620
around the world have been reading
the Exquisite Corpse episodes every

00:43:52.020 --> 00:44:32.040
two weeks.

00:43:13.000 --> 00:43:14.000


00:43:54.020 --> 00:43:55.020
[ Applause ]

00:43:56.020 --> 00:43:58.020
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Any questions?

00:43:58.020 --> 00:43:59.353
Oh, right over here.

00:44:00.020 --> 00:44:00.353
&gt;&gt; Which episode was your favorite?

00:44:02.020 --> 00:44:02.886
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: I'll
let the authors answer.

00:44:04.020 --> 00:44:06.086
Which episode, other than your
own episode, was your favorite?

00:44:06.020 --> 00:44:06.153
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: Oh, food.

00:44:08.020 --> 00:44:09.020
[ Laughter ]

00:44:10.020 --> 00:44:11.486
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Sorry, we'll
make it a little harder.

00:44:12.020 --> 00:44:12.553
Tobin, did you have
a favorite episode?

00:44:14.020 --> 00:44:14.220
&gt;&gt; M.T. Anderson: I loved the way

00:44:16.020 --> 00:44:16.686
that John Scieszka
began the whole thing.

00:44:18.020 --> 00:44:19.886
He just did a wonderful job.

00:44:20.020 --> 00:44:21.020
He's

00:44:22.020 --> 00:44:23.020
[ Applause ]

00:44:24.020 --> 00:44:25.553
&gt;&gt; M.T. Anderson: Yeah.

00:44:26.020 --> 00:44:28.553
He's not here, but yeah, he deserves
-- there was so much like energy

00:44:28.020 --> 00:44:30.420
and enthusiasm in his episode that
we all were very inspired by it.

00:44:30.020 --> 00:44:32.220
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson: I immediately
volunteered to do Chapter 2

00:44:32.020 --> 00:44:33.953
because I thought, well, I know
John's first chapter's going

00:44:34.020 --> 00:44:35.553
to be crazy and it's going
to get crazier and crazier,

00:44:36.020 --> 00:44:37.286
so I want to get in fast
before it gets too crazy.

00:44:38.020 --> 00:44:39.353
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Linda Sue,
did you have a favorite?

00:44:40.020 --> 00:44:42.153
&gt;&gt; Linda Sue: Well, I think that
Katherine had the hardest job.

00:44:42.020 --> 00:44:43.686
It was a pretty unwieldy
package with lots of tentacles.

00:44:44.020 --> 00:44:45.953
And she either wrapped them
neatly or just chopped them off.

00:44:46.020 --> 00:44:47.486
And I so admire the way that
she got the last chapter

00:44:48.020 --> 00:44:49.886
to pull everything together.

00:44:50.020 --> 00:44:51.686
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: And Tim, Tim
and James both did a number

00:44:52.020 --> 00:44:52.286
of illustrations for the episodes.

00:44:54.020 --> 00:44:56.020
Which was your favorite episode
to illustrate, Tim and James?

00:44:56.020 --> 00:44:58.220
&gt;&gt; Timothy Basil Ering: I think
the Cradle of Time was really --

00:44:58.020 --> 00:44:59.620
the Cradle of Time was just
like -- that was written --

00:45:00.020 --> 00:45:01.753
I loved every one of them.

00:45:02.020 --> 00:45:04.353
And the Gingerbread House, the
door -- all of them were super fun,

00:45:04.020 --> 00:45:05.753
but the Cradle of Time was
something just crazy and wild.

00:45:06.020 --> 00:45:06.486
That was one of my
favorites, I think.

00:45:08.020 --> 00:45:08.753
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: And
what about you, James?

00:45:10.020 --> 00:45:12.553
&gt;&gt; James Ransome: I'm going to say
that first, it was just a pleasure

00:45:12.020 --> 00:45:12.953
to work on all the
episodes that I worked on.

00:45:14.020 --> 00:45:15.620
But I think the Lemony Snicket
episode was my favorite.

00:45:16.020 --> 00:45:18.420
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Yes, Lemony Snicket
wrote two of the episodes, too.

00:45:18.020 --> 00:45:20.020
&gt;&gt; Yeah, which is really a lot
of fun, with the train crashes

00:45:20.020 --> 00:45:21.753
and all the different things
that he put in that episode.

00:45:22.020 --> 00:45:22.220
And it was just fun illustrating.

00:45:24.020 --> 00:45:25.753
But they're all wonderful.

00:45:26.020 --> 00:45:26.476
I still don't understand how the
writers can just sort of pick

00:45:29.630 --> 00:45:34.163
up where someone else left off and
create these crazy -- it's insane.

00:45:36.130 --> 00:45:39.263
A pig with a one eye
patch, the baby, the robot.

00:45:40.980 --> 00:45:42.780
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: The pirate.

00:45:42.980 --> 00:45:43.980
&gt;&gt; Arm-wrestling squid
or something like that.

00:45:44.980 --> 00:45:45.980
I mean.

00:45:46.980 --> 00:45:49.380
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: And I should say
that the reason we did this was --

00:45:48.980 --> 00:45:50.846
the way we did it with, we want
us to repeat that kind of game

00:45:51.180 --> 00:45:52.913
that you all play at home.

00:45:53.180 --> 00:45:54.846
You've played it at camp.

00:45:55.180 --> 00:45:55.513
You've played it on a stormy night.

00:45:57.180 --> 00:45:59.426
You've played it when the lights
have gone out, if you live up north

00:45:59.400 --> 00:46:00.186
and you get a winter
blackout, where one member

00:46:01.680 --> 00:46:05.946
of the family starts a story and
stops at a cliff-hanging moment,

00:46:05.970 --> 00:46:06.253
and then Aunt Margaret takes
up the next step, the next one,

00:46:09.620 --> 00:46:10.020
and then Cousin Tommy does the next,

00:46:11.620 --> 00:46:12.043
and then four-year-old
Benita does the next one.

00:46:14.330 --> 00:46:17.196
And we wanted to keep
that spontaneity to it

00:46:17.910 --> 00:46:18.060
so that pigs would feel free
to think, hey, this is a game

00:46:21.560 --> 00:46:24.560
that we play, and we can
write like this, too.

00:46:24.920 --> 00:46:26.853
That was a fabulous question.

00:46:26.920 --> 00:46:28.120
Thank you so much.

00:46:28.920 --> 00:46:30.186
We'll go over here.

00:46:30.920 --> 00:46:32.053
What's your name?

00:46:32.920 --> 00:46:33.986
&gt;&gt; Linda: Linda.

00:46:34.920 --> 00:46:35.786
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Linda,
what's your question?

00:46:36.920 --> 00:46:39.053
&gt;&gt; Linda: How come you gather up
here to start a huge festival?

00:46:38.920 --> 00:46:40.986
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: I'm sorry; Linda,
could you repeat that again?

00:46:40.920 --> 00:46:41.586
&gt;&gt; Linda: How come
you come to Washington

00:46:42.920 --> 00:46:44.853
and start up a huge festival?

00:46:44.920 --> 00:46:45.320
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: How
come you all come

00:46:46.920 --> 00:46:47.253
to Washington to this big festival?

00:46:48.920 --> 00:46:50.186
Why do you do that?

00:46:50.920 --> 00:46:52.053
&gt;&gt; Katherine Paterson:
Because it's so much fun.

00:46:52.920 --> 00:46:54.053
&gt;&gt; Fun, fun, fun.

00:46:54.920 --> 00:46:55.853
But did you ask how the
festival was started?

00:46:56.920 --> 00:46:57.043
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: How the
festival was started.

00:46:59.730 --> 00:47:01.123
I think John Cole, we'd have
to bring John Cole up to answer

00:47:02.270 --> 00:47:05.136
that question, how the
festival got started?

00:47:05.410 --> 00:47:08.810
Mr. Cole will be the expert
to give you that answer.

00:47:11.650 --> 00:47:14.183
&gt;&gt; John Cole: The festival
was started,

00:47:14.830 --> 00:47:19.163
came to us when Mrs. Laura Bush,
who was a reader and a librarian,

00:47:19.860 --> 00:47:19.956
helped us start the first
book festival and had the idea

00:47:23.430 --> 00:47:25.296
of bringing people together.

00:47:25.430 --> 00:47:29.096
And we are now able, after
ten years, to keep this going

00:47:29.510 --> 00:47:29.836
with the help of wonderful
groups like the ones

00:47:32.250 --> 00:47:32.360
and performers that
you've just seen.

00:47:34.540 --> 00:47:34.743
And we're very pleased to have
you all here, and let's close

00:47:38.270 --> 00:47:38.383
with one final round of applause
for my friends, the performers

00:47:42.290 --> 00:47:44.623
and the Exquisite Corpse Adventure.

00:47:45.960 --> 00:47:46.960
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:47:47.960 --> 00:47:48.960
Thanks a lot.

00:47:49.960 --> 00:47:50.360
&gt;&gt; John Cole: You were
all wonderful,

00:47:51.960 --> 00:47:53.130
and we will have one more
session a year from now

00:47:53.990 --> 00:47:54.730
at the next book festival, when
we not only will bring back some

00:47:57.450 --> 00:47:58.236
of the authors who have not
been part of the book festival,

00:48:00.530 --> 00:48:00.863
but we will have the book for sale.

00:48:02.530 --> 00:48:03.060
And as Mary Brigid said,
we can get it signed.

00:48:05.000 --> 00:48:05.533
Thank you all very
much, and thank you.

00:48:07.000 --> 00:48:08.000
[Applause]

00:48:09.000 --> 00:48:09.400
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Okay,
one more thing.

00:48:11.000 --> 00:48:12.600
&gt;&gt; Thank you, thank you.

00:48:13.000 --> 00:48:13.200
&gt;&gt; Mary Brigid: Those of you guys

00:48:15.000 --> 00:48:15.600
that didn't get your
questions answered,

00:48:17.000 --> 00:48:18.333
the autographing session
is from noon to 1 o'clock,

00:48:19.000 --> 00:48:21.333
and if you have further questions,
I'm sure authors would be happy

00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:23.000
to answer your questions then.

00:48:23.000 --> 00:48:25.400
And also, if you want to have a
winning program, make sure you head

00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:25.083
in that direction to
get your free copy

00:48:27.450 --> 00:48:30.183
of our White House
Looking In Looking Out.

00:48:31.400 --> 00:48:34.000
